name: GasCommodity
label: gas commodity
definition: extraction resource that is natural gas

name: ExtractionResource
label: extraction resource
definition: negotiable commodity that is a mineral resource obtained via withdrawal from the natural environment
explanatoryNote: These resources include ores, which contain commercially valuable amounts of metals, such as iron and aluminum, as well as precious metals, such as silver, gold, and platinum; precious stones, such as diamonds; building stones, such as granite; and solid fuels, such as coal and oil shale.

name: EnergyResource
label: energy resource
definition: negotiable commodity that is an energy-related product, or a derivative of an energy-related product, including electricity, renewable energy, or any power/energy delivered through a utility network of provider; diesel fuel, fuel oil, gas oil, gasoline, heating oil, jet fuel, kerosene, natural gas, oil (Brent, Tapis, Dubai, WTI)

name: PolypropyleneResource
definition: negotiable commodity including plastics
label: polypropylene resource

name: CommodityBasketConstituent
definition: component of a custom commodity basket whose relative importance with respect to other basket constituents is known
label: commodity basket constituent

name: BasketOfCommodities
label: basket of commodities
explanatoryNote: A commodity basket may contain constituents from one of the potential underlying assets or from multiple underlying assets.
definition: custom basket whose constituents consist of one or more negotiable commodities

name: CommodityForward
definition: forward contract in which a buyer and seller agree upon delivery of a specified quality and quantity of goods at a specified future date
label: commodity forward
explanatoryNote: Commodity forwards are often settled via cash transactions in many industries, including for the purposes of commodity merchandising. Terms may be more "personalized" than is the case with standardized futures contracts (i.e., delivery time and amount are as determined between seller and buyer). A price may be agreed upon in advance, or there may be agreement that the price will be determined at the time of delivery. A forward contract is a private and customizable agreement that settles at the end of the agreement and is traded over-the-counter.

name: CommodityDerivative
label: commodity derivative
definition: derivative instrument whose primary underlying notional item is a physical commodity, or the price, or related index, or any other aspect related to a physical commodity

name: CommodityUnderlyingAsset
label: commodity underlying asset
definition: underlier of a commodity derivative, including, but not limited to, the negotiable commodity itself
explanatoryNote: The underlying of a commodity swap may include a physical commodity, or the price, or behavior of the price, or any other aspect of a physical commodity.

name: PaperResource
label: paper resource
definition: negotiable commodity that is a paper product, including containerboard, newsprint, pulp, recovered paper

name: CommodityFuture
label: commodity future
definition: futures contract to buy or sell a predetermined amount of a commodity at a specific price on a specific date in the future
explanatoryNote: A commodity future is an agreement to purchase or sell a commodity for delivery in the future: (1) at a price that is determined at initiation of the contract; (2) that obligates each party to the contract to fulfill the contract at the specified price; (3) that is used to assume or shift price risk; and (4) that may be satisfied by delivery or offset.

name: OilCommodity
definition: generated resource that is a viscous liquid derived from petroleum, including for use as fuel, or as a lubricant, and the manufacture of many types of paints, plastics, and other materials
label: oil commodity

name: GeneratedResource
definition: negotiable commodity obtained via some generation process, including electricity, renewable energy, or any power/energy delivered through a utility network or provider
label: generated resource

name: ServiceResource
label: service resource
definition: negotiable commodity involving services such as transportation, communications, and trade

name: CommodityReturnLeg
label: commodity return leg
explanatoryNote: The cash flows from a commodity may be negative as you have a cost from holding the commodity but there are no interim cash flows, so it equates to a negative interest rate. So a commodity swap is like a TRS in that it is based on the return on the increase in value.
definition: leg of a commodity return swap in which the return is based on a physical commodity, or the price, or behavior of the price, or any other aspect related to a physical commodity

name: Metal
label: metal
definition: material that, when freshly prepared, polished, or fractured, shows a lustrous appearance, and conducts electricity and heat relatively well

name: AgriculturalResource
definition: negotiable commodity that is obtained via some agricultural process, including forestry, fishing, livestock, grain, dairy, corn, cocoa, soybeans, sugar, coffee
label: agricultural resource

name: CommodityOption
label: commodity option
definition: option where the option buyer has the right to buy or sell specified commodities or commodity related index at a fixed price or formula, on or before a specified date

name: FertilizerResource
label: fertilizer resource
definition: negotiable commodity that includes ammonia, diammonium phosphate (DAP), potash, sulphur, urea, urea and ammonium nitrate (UAN)

name: CommodityIndex
label: commodity index
definition: investment vehicle that tracks a basket of commodities to measure their price and investment return performance

name: WeatherDerivative
definition: derivative instrument whose primary underlying notional item is based on something related to the weather, for example, the average temperature in Chicago in January
label: weather derivative
explanatoryNote: Such a derivative can be used to hedge risks related to the demand for heating fuel or electricity. The underlying 'asset' is not a negotiable commodity per se, but because the weather can impact the prices and other things related to other commodities, weather derivatives are treated as commodity derivatives for regulatory purposes.

name: CommoditySpotContract
label: commodity spot contract
definition: contract that involves physical delivery of the commodity asset at settlement

name: CommoditySwap
explanatoryNote: Commodity swaps typically involve the exchange of a floating commodity price for a set price over an agreed-upon period.
definition: commodity derivative that includes, without limitation, any swap for which the primary underlying notional item is a physical commodity, or the price, or behavior of the price, or the level of a commodity index, or other aspect related to a physical commodity
label: commodity swap

name: Bullion
label: bullion
explanatoryNote: Physical metals fall into two categories: (1) bullion, which are coins, ingots or bars of a specific weight and purity; and (2) "numismatic" or collectible coins, which can be rare or old coins, or special proofs that are newly minted as collectibles. If a particular asset is identified as "numismatic" or "collectible", it is, by definition, not considered bullion aside from its melt value.
definition: physical precious metal that is officially recognized as being at least 99.5 percent pure

name: FreightResource
label: freight resource
definition: negotiable commodity that is a freight index route

name: IndustrialResource
definition: negotiable commodity that is obtained via some industrial process, including construction and manufacturing
label: industrial resource

name: EnvironmentalResource
label: environmental resource
definition: negotiable commodity including offset credits

name: BaseMetal
definition: common metal that tarnishes, oxidizes, or corrodes relatively quickly when exposed to air or moisture, that is widely used in commercial and industrial applications, such as construction and manufacturing
explanatoryNote: Base metals or alloys include metals other than precious metals, such as copper, lead, zinc, tin, iron, steel, or brass. Note that iron and steel are included under metal and metal products in some classification schemes - see  for example.
label: base metal

name: EnergyTransmissionRights
definition: rights to the transmission of power across an electricity distribution network
label: energy transmission rights

name: GrainCommodity
definition: agricultural resource that is a small, hard seed, of a food plant, especially of a cereal plant, such as wheat, corn, rye, oats, rice, and millet
label: grain commodity

name: MeatCommodity
label: meat commodity
definition: agricultural resource derived from the flesh of an animal (especially a mammal), such as pork bellies

name: OilGrade
definition: measure of the viscosity of oil during operation
label: oil grade

name: hasCommodityValueAsOfDate
definition: indicates the per unit value of a given commodity as of some specified date
label: has commodity value as of date

name: hasGrade
definition: The grade of oil e.g. Brent Crude.
label: has grade
